85
00:06:22,800 --> 00:06:29,230
It follows that an ab initio description of
the nuclear force stays very difficult,

86
00:06:29,230 --> 00:06:34,470
although we dispose of
a well-established quantum theory for

87
00:06:34,470 --> 00:06:40,534
interaction between quarks and gluons,
namely QCD.

88
00:06:40,534 --> 00:06:44,680
At short distances,
comparable to the hadron size,

89
00:06:44,680 --> 00:06:49,853
the exchange of gluons produces
a potential between quark and antiquark 

90
00:06:49,853 --> 00:06:56,010
which is similar to the one established
by photons in a positronium bound state.

91
00:06:56,010 --> 00:07:02,600
This potential varies with distance as
1/r like the Coulomb potential.

92
00:07:02,600 --> 00:07:05,080
At large distances,
there is a different behavior,

93
00:07:05,080 --> 00:07:08,270
the potential becomes
larger with distance.

94
00:07:08,270 --> 00:07:13,070
We already saw a potential that fits
the description of the spectra of J/Psi and

95
00:07:13,070 --> 00:07:15,875
Upsilon states in video 5.3.

96
00:07:16,980 --> 00:07:22,040
The second term determines the behavior
of the long range potential with

97
00:07:22,040 --> 00:07:27,410
a constant K equal to
about 1 GeV/fm.

98
00:07:28,550 --> 00:07:31,940
This corresponds to a constant
long distance force

99
00:07:31,940 --> 00:07:35,820
equivalent to the one required
to lift a weight of 16 tons.

100
00:07:37,530 --> 00:07:41,710
The second term is created by
the interaction between gluons.

101
00:07:41,710 --> 00:07:43,750
In terms of a chromostatic language,

102
00:07:43,750 --> 00:07:49,100
the additional force between gluons
concentrates the color field

103
00:07:49,100 --> 00:07:53,130
along a corridor that connects
the two color charges.

104
00:07:53,130 --> 00:07:56,110
Because of the particular
shape of the field,

105
00:07:56,110 --> 00:08:00,530
one also call this a string
that connects the colors.

106
00:08:00,530 --> 00:08:03,700
The potential proportional to

107
00:08:03,700 --> 00:08:08,810
k times r does not allow color and
anti-color to be separated,

108
00:08:08,810 --> 00:08:13,241
but confines them to distances
of the order of 1 fm.

109
00:08:15,630 --> 00:08:20,070
The potential inside hadrons ought
to be generated dynamically

110
00:08:20,070 --> 00:08:23,660
by the interaction between the quarks and
gluons.

111
00:08:23,660 --> 00:08:28,600
Obtaining results is complicated by
difficulties which are both conceptual and

112
00:08:28,600 --> 00:08:30,080
technical.

113
00:08:30,080 --> 00:08:33,750
Both the confinement of color
at large distance and

114
00:08:33,750 --> 00:08:38,650
the relativistic and quasi-free movement
of quarks must be incorporated.

115
00:08:38,650 --> 00:08:42,870
One must treat states with
multiple quarks and gluons.

116
00:08:42,870 --> 00:08:45,060
The evolution of the strong coupling

117
00:08:46,200 --> 00:08:51,970
constant alpha_strong with four-momentum transfer
q^2 must be taken into account.

118
00:08:51,970 --> 00:08:54,490
We will talk about this
effect in a moment.

119
00:08:55,630 --> 00:08:59,970
Calculation techniques are considerably
simplified if one replaces

120
00:08:59,970 --> 00:09:05,660
the space-time continuum by a mesh
of equidistant discrete points,

121
00:09:05,660 --> 00:09:09,487
similar to a crystal lattice with sides a.

122
00:09:09,487 --> 00:09:14,960
One defines the quark fields
on the sites of the lattice,

123
00:09:14,960 --> 00:09:17,180
and gluon fields on the links.

124
00:09:17,180 --> 00:09:22,240
The continuum of space-time is recovered
in the limit of an infinitely large lattice

125
00:09:22,240 --> 00:09:25,030
with a -> 0.

126
00:09:25,030 --> 00:09:29,485
This discretization introduces
a lower limit on momentum-transfer

127
00:09:29,485 --> 00:09:31,860
of the order of 1/a,

128
00:09:31,860 --> 00:09:37,810
and thus regularizes the divergences
inherent to pertulative QCD.

129
00:09:37,810 --> 00:09:42,540
Numerical calculations of this kind
require tremendous computing resources.

130
00:09:42,540 --> 00:09:46,674
They are performed on the most
powerful supercomputers.

131
00:09:46,674 --> 00:09:50,600
With this non-perturbative method,
one arrives, fo

132
00:09:50,600 --> 00:09:56,200
example, at results for
the spectrum of light hadrons.

133
00:09:56,200 --> 00:10:01,450
The calculated masses are the average for
the different particle types.

134
00:10:01,450 --> 00:10:05,940
For instance, the mass of nucleon is
the average of the mass of the proton and

135
00:10:05,940 --> 00:10:07,440
the neutron.

136
00:10:07,440 --> 00:10:12,390
Parameters of the calculation are the
strong coupling constant, alpha_strong,

137
00:10:12,390 --> 00:10:17,350
and the masses of light quarks up and
down, and the quark strange.

138
00:10:17,350 --> 00:10:22,579
They are fixed using the measured
mass of pions, kaons and 

139
00:10:22,579 --> 00:10:24,611
Xi as reference.

140
00:10:24,611 --> 00:10:29,840
This results in a pretty
impressive understanding of

141
00:10:29,840 --> 00:10:35,240
the hadron spectrum, suggesting that
QCD is indeed a correct theory for

142
00:10:35,240 --> 00:10:40,182
strong interaction also
at larger distances.

143
00:10:40,182 --> 00:10:44,684
Distance laws for
electromagnetic and

144
00:10:44,684 --> 00:10:48,570
strong interaction are fundamentally different.

145
00:10:48,570 --> 00:10:54,536
The electromagnetic potential decreases
as 1/r as a function of distance.

146
00:10:54,536 --> 00:11:00,044
The strong potential increases at
long distances proportional to r.

147
00:11:00,044 --> 00:11:02,361
To understand this difference,

148
00:11:02,361 --> 00:11:07,690
we must consider quantum correction
to the photon and to the gluon propagators.

149
00:11:07,690 --> 00:11:12,020
A significant correction to the photon propagator

150
00:11:12,020 --> 00:11:16,280
is the one which introduces
an electron-positron loop.

151
00:11:16,280 --> 00:11:23,010
This loop creates additional electric
charges between the projectile and target.

152
00:11:23,010 --> 00:11:25,440
We call this phenomenon
vacuum polarization.

153
00:11:25,440 --> 00:11:29,670
In electrostatic language we
can say that these additional

154
00:11:29,670 --> 00:11:32,008
charges screen the target charge.

155
00:11:32,008 --> 00:11:35,830
Therefore the effective charge
decreases with distance.

156
00:11:37,110 --> 00:11:41,520
That is, it increases with
growing momentum transfer q^2.

157
00:11:41,520 --> 00:11:44,880
This is, indeed,
what we find experimentally.

158
00:11:44,880 --> 00:11:48,200
For electrodynamics,
this is a small effect.

159
00:11:48,200 --> 00:11:52,960
To see a change of alpha of a few percent,
we have to compare momentum

160
00:11:52,960 --> 00:11:57,730
transfer at almost zero that
is at very large distances,

161
00:11:57,730 --> 00:12:02,090
where alpha is measured
to be about 1/137

162
00:12:02,090 --> 00:12:06,882
– see the example of the Penning
trap in video 4.3 –

163
00:12:06,882 --> 00:12:11,629
to the energy of the Large Electron
Positron collider at CERN,

164
00:12:11,629 --> 00:12:18,700
where the momentum transfer q^2
is around 10^4 GeV^2.

165
00:12:18,700 --> 00:12:22,410
That is at very short distances.

166
00:12:24,630 --> 00:12:29,660
For strong interactions, the effect
of vacuum polarisation is much more

167
00:12:29,660 --> 00:12:34,790
pronounced. Because of the size
of the strong coupling, the vacuum polarization

168
00:12:34,790 --> 00:12:39,800
and the change in the net charge
with distance are more important.

169
00:12:39,800 --> 00:12:44,080
In addition,
the sign of the effect is reversed.

170
00:12:44,080 --> 00:12:48,020
The strong force becomes
stronger with distance.

171
00:12:48,020 --> 00:12:53,600
This is because there are two types of
vacuum polarization graphs for gluons.

172
00:12:53,600 --> 00:12:58,450
The analogue of electromagnetic
polarization introduces quark-antiquark

173
00:12:58,450 --> 00:13:03,500
loops in the gluon propagator
which shield the colors charge.

174
00:13:03,500 --> 00:13:07,150
But in addition,
the coupling of gluons between them

175
00:13:07,150 --> 00:13:11,390
introduces gluon loops which
have the opposite sign.

176
00:13:11,390 --> 00:13:15,730
And in the chromostatic language,
we can say that the gluon loops

177
00:13:15,730 --> 00:13:19,670
introduce additional color-anticolor
charges which are attractive.

178
00:13:20,720 --> 00:13:26,090
This reinforces the color charge of
the target instead of shielding it.

179
00:13:26,090 --> 00:13:28,910
Because of the large number of gluons, and

180
00:13:28,910 --> 00:13:34,500
their zero mass, gluon loops dominate
the strong vacuum polarization.

181
00:13:35,760 --> 00:13:39,589
Consequently, the color charge
of the target increases with

182
00:13:39,589 --> 00:13:43,720
distance proportional to the inverse
of the momentum transfer.

183
00:13:43,720 --> 00:13:48,477
Indeed one experimentally 
finds that this effect is

184
00:13:48,477 --> 00:13:53,441
more significant than its
electromagnetic counterpart.

185
00:13:53,441 --> 00:13:58,390
In the next video we will see
how these properties of strong

186
00:13:58,390 --> 00:14:02,330
interaction keep us from
seeing free quarks.

